    <text>
        <body>
            <head>113. Letter From the Assistant Secretary of State for European Affairs (<persName
                    corresp="reccVKFbVuxnI4007">Ridgway</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d113fn1">Source: Reagan Library,
                        <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> Papers, Box 21, 1985
                    Sept Mtg w/ Shev. Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1985-09-28"
                        >September 28, 1985</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Mr. Secretary:</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I asked Jim <persName corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName> to do a
                preliminary analysis of the Soviet proposal<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d113fn2"
                    >Reference is to <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>’s
                    letter of September 12, which <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc"
                        >Shevardnadze</persName> handed <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                        >Reagan</persName> in a September 27 meeting in the White House, following a
                    meeting with <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> on
                    September 25. In it, <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>
                    proposed that “the two sides agree to a complete ban on space attack weapons and
                    a truly radical <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reduction</rs>, say
                    by 50 percent, of their corresponding nuclear arms.” (Reagan Library, Executive
                    Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                    </gloss>: Head of State Files, <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>: General
                    Secretary <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName> (851009))
                    The letter and memoranda of these conversations are scheduled for publication in
                        <ref target="frus1981-88v05#d84">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. V,
                        Soviet Union, March 1985–October 1986, Documents 84</ref>, <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v05#d99">99</ref>, and <ref target="frus1981-88v05#d105"
                        >105</ref>.</note> (attached). Two bottom lines: (1) reductions in the
                Soviets’ own forces are real, but the deal is inequitable as our forces would be
                affected even more; (2) the vulnerability of <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >U.S.</placeName>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> would increase; we could not go mobile with our existing <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> as new types are barred.</p>
            <p>However, as <persName corresp="rec2p5eZ5kgeXCRJ4">Bud</persName> commented last
                night, this is the Soviets’ ingoing position and there are elements we can work
                with.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Rozanne L. <persName corresp="reccVKFbVuxnI4007"
                            >Ridgway</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d113fn3">
                        <persName corresp="reccVKFbVuxnI4007">Ridgway</persName> signed the letter
                        “Roz” above her typed signature.</note>
                </signed>
            </closer>
            <pb facs="0451" n="424" xml:id="pg_424"/>
            <frus:attachment xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
                <note>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Attachment</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Paper Prepared in the Department of State</hi>
                    <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d113fn4">Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1985-09-28">September 28, 1985</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rendition="simple_centre">
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Preliminary Analysis of the Soviet Proposal</hi>
                </p>
                <p>From the outlines of the Soviet counterproposal that <persName
                        corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName> has sketched, it is
                    possible to make preliminary assessments of the forces on both sides that would
                    likely result from such an approach:</p>
                <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Soviet Forces</p>
                <p>The Soviets would probably allocate their 6000 “charges” roughly as follows:</p>
                <table cols="2">
                    <row>
                        <cell>—3500</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                                <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                            </gloss>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>. This would
                            represent a substantial cut from the current level of about 6500 and
                            projected levels of 10,000–12,000 by the mid-1990’s.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>—2000</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                                <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBM</rs>
                            </gloss>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>. This is a
                            bit below current levels, and about half the projected 1990’s
                            level.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>—500</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs> weapons. Again
                            below current (750) and projected (1200) levels.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>So the reductions would be real. The character of the force, however, would not
                    change. It would continue to be dominated by large <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>. The Soviets would no doubt keep and modernize a large number of <rs
                        corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky" type="topic">SS–18</rs>’s, and continue
                    deployment of SS–24’s and <rs type="topic" corresp="recMS3hu34UIPBB1l"
                        >SS–25</rs>’s (despite the freeze on new systems).</p>
                <p>As for <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                    </gloss>, the Soviets probably project <placeName corresp="rec3Gz23Bw0AZRDOQ"
                        >British</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO"
                        >French</placeName> missile forces will have 1000–1200 <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> when their <gloss
                        target="#t_MIRV_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRV</rs>
                    </gloss> programs are complete, so they could keep up to 400 <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recibQAICNR8y1pTK">SS–20</rs>’s.</p>
                <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> Forces</p>
                <p>The 6000 limit is probably intended to apply to <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recAt16KRrnQ3ZDPG">theater-nuclear forces</rs> (<gloss
                        target="#t_GLCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recEYJpmEGRfvJpPc" type="topic">GLCM</rs>
                    </gloss>, <rs type="topic" corresp="recj3V5JyPN7ZoaIK">P–II</rs>, F–111,
                    carrier-based aircraft, etc.) as well as <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic forces</rs>. Since there is no chance
                    the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> would accept this
                    approach (which the Soviets have advanced off-and-on since 1969), it would be
                    pointless to include such forces in an illustrative <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> total. It should be borne in
                    mind, however, that the apparent Soviet proposal would count such forces against
                    the 6000 limit.</p>
                <pb facs="0452" n="425" xml:id="pg_425"/>
                <p>Even confined to <rs type="topic" corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic
                        forces</rs> alone, a ceiling of 6000 charges would squeeze the <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> much harder than the Soviets,
                    because we rely much more on <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bombers</rs>, and the <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bombers</rs> need large numbers of weapons to overcome defenses. A
                    representative <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName> force might
                    be:</p>
                <table cols="2">
                    <row>
                        <cell>—1000</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                                <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                            </gloss>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> (½ the
                            current total and 1/3 the projected total with 100 <rs
                                corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M-X</rs>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>—3000</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                                <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBM</rs>
                            </gloss>
                            <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss> (about ½ the current total)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>—2000</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs> weapons (<gloss
                                target="#t_ALCM_1">
                                <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                            </gloss>, <gloss target="#t_SRAM_1">
                                <rs type="topic" corresp="recJJ92wdIeZoqUpd">SRAM</rs>
                            </gloss>, bombs). This would be less than half the current total. There
                            would be no constraints on <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq"
                                >modernization</rs> or expansion of the defenses <rs type="topic"
                                corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> face.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>The <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs> constraint
                    would preclude the small <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                    </gloss>, the <rs type="topic" corresp="recbgJJiOGydQB0ct">D–5</rs>
                    <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBM</rs>
                    </gloss>, and possibly the <gloss target="#t_MX_2">
                        <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M–X</rs>
                    </gloss>. <gloss target="#t_GLCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recEYJpmEGRfvJpPc" type="topic">GLCM</rs>
                    </gloss> and <rs type="topic" corresp="recj3V5JyPN7ZoaIK">P–II</rs> would either
                    be withdrawn from <placeName corresp="recp8rWUqC6nWf8T5">Europe</placeName> or
                    counted against the 6000 limit.</p>
                <p>The net result of the use of charges as the primary unit of account, and
                    inequitable treatment of theater forces, is that the Soviet proposal would force
                    much deeper reductions for the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                        >US</placeName> than for the Soviets. We could keep a substantial force of
                        <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBMs</rs>
                    </gloss> (but could not give them hard-target capability), but only at the
                    expense of drastic <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                    </gloss> and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs>
                    reductions. Our confidence in <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                        >bomber</rs> penetration would be reduced.</p>
                <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Other Comments</p>
                <p>Some elements of the Soviet proposal (<gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                    </gloss> ban, <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="recK25AUjO3toNZWX">ASAT</rs>
                    </gloss> ban) would be extremely difficult to verify, and many other important
                    provisions would require <rs type="topic" corresp="recLpQ8TqRD7uhfnH"
                        >cooperative measures</rs> for <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                        >verification</rs>.</p>
                <p>The Soviet <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">strategic
                        defense</rs> program would continue. The <placeName
                        corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">strategic defense initiative</rs>
                    would be drastically curtailed.</p>
            </frus:attachment>
